\section{Vote-Sellers and Vote-Buyers: Two Sides of the Same Coin?}

% general hook on advanced democracies, and the decline on clientelism// US Context.
Many advanced democracies were first very clientelistic political systems. For instance, \citet[200]{Stokes:2013cj} explains that in the nineteenth-century United States ``vote buying was commonplace.'' In Chicago, New York City, Newark, and other big cities, votes were exchanged for ``cash, food, alcohol, health care, poverty relief, and myriad other benefits,''\footnote{\citet[200]{Stokes:2013cj}.} even resembling the worst practices in the current developing world. The street price of the right to vote freely seemed to be very low. Bensel explains that ``[voters] handed in a party ticket in return for a shot of whiskey, a pair of boots, or a small amount of money.''\footnote{In \citet[227]{Stokes:2013cj}.} Vote buying, besides being cheap, was ``the major urban political institution in the late nineteenth century''\footnote{\citet[2]{Erie:1990aa}.} in ``one-half of the nation's twenty largest cities.''\footnote{\citet[2]{Erie:1990aa}.} Students of American political development have analyzed vote-buying in more detail, confirming both its early development, and its generalized practice.\footnote{See particularly \citet{Bensel:2004aa} and \citet{Campbell:2005aa}. For the British case during the Victorian Era, see \citet{Kam2016b}.} However, nowadays vote-buying seems to have declined considerably.  For instance, \citet[201]{Stokes:2013cj} have shown that industrialization has driven up the median income of the electorate, making vote-buying more expensive for party machines.\footnote{However, see \citet[320]{Kitschelt2007}, who explain that ``it is not economic development that accounts for the emergence and decline of varying linkage practices and not even the nature of formal democratic institutions,'' but higher levels of ``[s]tate involvement in the public sector.''} In line with that, \autoref{fig:lapop:bar:chart:plot} suggests---using survey data from the U.S.---that $\Sexpr{round(as.numeric(as.numeric(table(clientelism)["Never"]) * 100) / lapop.bar.chart.N, 1)}$\% of respondents have \emph{never} received a clientelistic offer from a political party.\footnote{A very small percentage ($\Sexpr{round(as.numeric(as.numeric(table(clientelism)["Often"]) + as.numeric(table(clientelism)["Sometimes"]) * 100 ) / lapop.bar.chart.N, 1)}$\%) reports to have received some kind of clientelistic offer from a political party.}


% Hook 1
We seem to know that vote-\emph{buyers} cannot afford this strategy any longer, not at least in a massive scale, thus making vote-buying a rare event. However, several questions remain unanswered. And worryingly, most of them pertain to vote-\emph{sellers}. \emph{What would voters do, if offered the chance to sell their votes? Would they sell their votes (and at what price), or would they consistently opt-out of vote-selling? What are the micro-foundations of vote-selling?}\footnote{In a similar vein, \citet{Weitz-shapiro} explains that vote-buyers in Argentina would opt-out of clientelism in scenarios where the middle class, due to ``moral or normative'' reasons, would /fail to support clientelistic politicians.} Given that the emphasis so far has been devoted to studying vote-\emph{buying}, ignoring the micro-dynamics of vote-\emph{selling}, prior studies do not offer satisfactory answers to these questions.\footnote{\citet{Hicken2015,Hicken2018} constitute two very important exceptions.} 

% Hook 2



Prior research usually focuses on whether \emph{parties} have attempted to buy votes, overlooking the question of whether citizens would \emph{sell} their votes. For instance, \autoref{fig:lapop:bar:chart:plot} shows responses about whether \emph{a candidate or someone from a political party} has offered something in exchange for people's votes, completely ignoring the \emph{supply} side. The figure, in fact, represents the canon in the clientelism literature, begging the question about whether survey respondents answering  ``never'' (been offered to \emph{buy} their votes), would still be \emph{willing} to \emph{sell} their votes. I contend that this \emph{demand-side bias} gives an incomplete picture. Overlooking the supply side should give the falsely optimistic impression that U.S. voters systematically \emph{oppose} vote-buying, ``thus'' engaging almost \emph{never} in clientelism (as \autoref{fig:lapop:bar:chart:plot} strongly suggests). Moreover, demand-side studies of clientelism have traditionally focused, except for a few exceptions,\footnote{Notably, \citet{Zarazaga2015a} interviewed 120 brokers in Argentina. \citet{Szwarcberg2013} employed a similar strategy. \citet{Oliveros2016} interviewed 1,184 lower-and mid-level local public sector employees in three Argentinean municipalities about the provision of favors. See also \citet{Stokes:2013cj}. Vote-selling has been studied in other regions as well, such as Lebanon (\citet{Corstange2012a}), Philippines (\citet{Hicken2015a,Hicken2018}), and Nigeria (\citet{Bratton2008a}).} on what \emph{parties} do by asking \emph{voters} about what \emph{parties} do. This \emph{reverse demand-side bias} might cause other problems too. For instance, not only asking (directly) survey respondents about illegal behaviors constitutes an important source of social desirability bias,\footnote{Actually suggesting that the number \emph{never}(s) should be larger. See \citet{Gonzalez-Ocantos2012}. However, and unfortunately, their focus is on vote-\emph{buying}, overlooking vote-\emph{selling} too. They ask whether ``candidates or activists gave [voters] a gift or did a favor.''} double-biasing these results. Also, learning \emph{indirectly} about what parties do by asking voters, poses a number problems to causal inference. At least, individual responses should be  confounded with personal frustrations and/or negative opinions about political parties and politics in general.


