Beyond their geographical location, however, the objective of this study is to learn about the micro-dynamics of vote-sellers, including what socio-economic variables are more associated with vote-selling.\footnote{The \texttt{R} package \texttt{list} was used (\citet{Blair2015}). The estimation method used was ``\text{\Sexpr{method}}'' while the maximum number of iterations was \Sexpr{format(round(as.numeric(maxIter), 0), nsmall=0, big.mark=",")}. The rest of the arguments were left at their default values.} While there are a number of important factors that explain vote-selling, the motivation of the model presented here is to provide an overview of the phenomenon. Considering that, four covariates were included; namely, income, education, party identification, and political ideology. These variables have been widely considered in the clientelism literature.\footnote{\citet{Nazareno2008a,GonzalezOcantos2014}. But also see \citet{Bahamonde:2017ad}. See also \citet{Weitz-shapiro}.} Each variable was estimated twice, i.e. one model per treatment (``low''/``high'').\footnote{The regression table is \autoref{tab:regression}.} 


